document.docTitle: Zetzellia agistzellia Hernandes & Feres, sp. n.
document.masterDocTitle: Two new species of Zetzellia Oudemans (Acari: Stigmaeidae) that threaten the concept of genera: disgeneric marriage?

mods:titleInfo.mods:title: Two new species of Zetzellia Oudemans (Acari: Stigmaeidae) that threaten the concept of genera: disgeneric marriage?

heading.emphasis:
Zetzellia agistzellia Hernandes & Feres
sp. n. (
Figs. 1–22
)

subSubSection.paragraph:
This species resembles
Z. silvicola Gonzalez
,
Z. antipoda Wood
and
Z. gonzalezi Wood. All
four have dorsal shields reticulated, the dorsal pair
c 1
born on the main shield, and share several aspects of leg chaetotaxy.
Zetzellia antipoda
and
Z. gonzalezi
are very similar to each other, differing only in the length of setae ve , and the size of polygons of dorsal shields, a little larger in
Z . gonzalezi
. According to
Wood ( 1967 )
, they can only be accurately distinguished with close examination side by side. Concerning the length of dorsal setae,
Z. agistzellia
appears to be at an intermediate position between
Z. silvicola
, which has the shortest setae of them, almost half the length of those of
Z. agistzellia
and the two species described by Wood.
Zetzellia agistzellia
and
Z. silvicola
share almost all aspects of leg chaetotaxy, except tarsus I, which has 13 setae (rather than 12 in
Z . silvicola
). Additional differences:
Z. agistzellia
with two pairs of aggenital setae (only one pair in
Z. silvicola
) and with small size of dorsal polygons (a little larger in
Z. agistzellia
). The two species of Wood have one fewer seta on femur IV, but one more on tarsus IV. The three latter species are similar concerning the size of dorsal polygons.

Additional characters of
Z. agistzellia
are: dorsal setae serrate, subequal in length; prodorsal shield trapezoidal and rounded in outline, bearing 3 pairs of setae ( vi , ve and sci ); pairs
h 1
and
h
2
set on the same terminal shield; tegument ventral and around dorsal shields finely striated; orange coloured when alive; eggs spherical, bright dark yellow. Solenidia (on tibiae and tarsus), supracoxal setae (on coxae) and famulus (on genua) are referred in parenthesis.

FIGURES 1–7 :
Zetzellia agistzellia
sp. n. (female) 1. dorsum, 2. anogenital region, ventral, 3. palp, 4–7. legs I–IV.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Female (n= 7 ) (
Figs. 1–7
). Dorsum . Dorsal shields reticulated; prodorsal shield bearing three pairs of setae ( vi , ve and sci ); hysterosomal shield bearing 4 pairs of setae (
c 1
,
d 1
,
e 1
and
e 2
); seta
d 2
on satellite platelets. Venter . With 3 pairs of ventral setae (
1 a
,
3 a
and
4 a
) between coxae II, III and IV, respectively; genitoanal valves each with 4 setae (
g 1
,
ps 1–3
);
ps 3
short, thick and serrate;
ag 1
inserted on platelet near anal opening;
ag 2
inserted on the striated tegument. Gnathosoma . With two pairs of slender setae on subcapitulum, extending to anterior half of palpfemur; eupathidium at distal palptarsus trifid. Palp chaetotaxy: coxa: 3 ( 2 subcapitular plus seta e ); trochanter: 0; femur: 3 ; genu: 1 ; tibia: 3 setae plus claw; tarsus 4 setae. Legs . Chaetotaxy (I–IV): coxae 2 ( 1 )­ 1­2 ­ 2 ; trochanters 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ; femora 5 ­ 4 ­ 2 ­ 2 ; genua 3 ( 1 )­ 1 ­0­0; tibiae 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 ); tarsi 12 ( 1 )­ 9 ( 1 )­ 7 ( 1 )­ 7 .
Developmental changes [from deutonymph female]: addition of 1 seta on trochanter IV and 1 genital seta (g 1 ).

caption.paragraph:
FIGURES 8–14 :
Zetzellia agistzellia
sp. n. (male) 8. dorsum, 9. anogenital region, ventral, 10. palp, 11–14. legs I–IV.

subSubSection.paragraph:
Male (n= 3 ). (
Figs. 8–14
). Dorsum . Dorsal shields reticulated; prodorsal shield as in female; hysterosomal shield bearing 6 pairs of setae (
c 1
,
d 1
,
d 2
,
e 1
,
e 2
and
f 1
);
h 1
slightly reduced, the shortest of dorsal setae. Venter . Ventral setae as in female;
ps 1
short and thin, each inserted on a tubercle, being visible dorsally due to the curvature of this region; aggenital setae asimetrically set. Gnathosoma . As female. Legs . Chaetotaxy (I–IV): coxae 2 ( 1 )­ 1­2 ­ 2 ; trochanters 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ; femora 5 ­ 4 ­ 2 ­ 2 ; genua 3 ( 1 )­ 1 ­0­0; tibiae 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 ); tarsi 12 ( 2 )­ 9 ( 2 )­ 7 ( 1 )­ 7 ( 1 ).

Developmental changes [from deutonymph male]: hysterosomal shield includes pair
f 1
; one additional seta on trochanter IV, and 1 solenidum on tarsi I, II and IV; there is no alteration in neither anal nor aggenital setae. The presence of 6 pairs of setae on the hyterosomal shield is typical of males of
Agistemus
, as well as the reduced
e 1
. In this species, however,
e 1
is not significantly reduced.

Deutonymph female. (n= 3 ). (
Figs. 19–20
). Dorsum (
Fig. 19
). Dorsal setae as in adult female. Venter . Ventral and aggenital setae as in female (except pair
g 1
, absent). Gnathosoma . As in female. Legs . Chaetotaxy (I–IV): coxae 2 ( 1 )­ 1­2 ­ 2 ; trochanters 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ­0; femora 5 ­ 4 ­ 2 ­ 2 ; genua 3 ( 1 )­ 1 ­0­0; tibiae 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 ); tarsi 12 ( 1 )­ 9 ( 1 )­ 7 ( 1 )­ 7 .
Developmental changes [from protonymph]: addition of 2 setae on coxa IV, 1 seta on trochanters I, II and III, 1 seta on femora I and IV and on tarsi IV.

Deutonymph male. (n= 2 ). (
Figs. 21­22
). Dorsum (
Fig. 21
). Hysterosomal shield bears 5 pairs of setae (
c 1
,
d 1 d 2
,
e 1
and
e 2
). Venter . Ventral and aggenital setae as in deutonymph female;
ps 3
shortest of anal setae. There is no alteration in aggenital nor anal setae in the moulting to adult male. Gnathosoma . As in female. Legs . Chaetotaxy (I–IV): coxae 2 ( 1 )­ 1­2 ­ 2 ; trochanters 1 ­ 1 ­ 1 ­0; femora 5 ­ 4 ­ 2 ­ 2 ; genua 3 ( 1 )­ 1 ­0­0; tibiae 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 ); tarsi 12 ( 1 )­ 9 ( 1 )­ 7 ( 1 )­ 7 .

Developmental changes [from protonymph]: the inclusion of seta
d 2
on the hysterosomal shield distinguishes this form (male) from the deutonymph female; in the next moult to adulthood, male hysterosomal shield also includes the pair
f 1
; same leg chaetotaxy as in deutonymph female.
Developmental changes [from larva]: addition of leg IV; addition of one ventral seta on coxae I and II, and two ventral setae on coxa III.

Larva (n= 5 ). (
Figs. 15–16
). Dorsum . Prodorsal shield smooth, partly invaded by tegumental striae along median line; dorsal setae set on isolated platelets, no hysterosomal shield; setae
e 1
and
e
2
set on the same platelet; median transversal ridge dividing prodorsum and hysterosoma. Venter . 2 pairs of ventral setae (
1 a
and
3 a
) between coxae II and III, respectively; 3 pairs of anal setae,
ps 3
the shortest and
ps 1
a little slender than other anals; setae
ag 1­2
and
g 1
absent. Gnathosoma . As in adult female, except palpfemur with 2 setae, and palpcoxa, with 2 setae ( 1 subcapitular plus seta e ). Legs . Chaetotaxy (I–IV): coxae 1 ( 1 )­0­0; trochanters 0­0­0; femora 4 ­ 4 ­ 2 ; genua 2 ( 1 )­ 1 ­0; tibiae 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 )­ 5 ( 1 ); tarsi 12 ( 1 )­ 9 ( 1 )­ 7 ( 1 ).

Zetzellia agistzellia

subSubSection.paragraph:
Remarks : This species inhabits mostly the base of rubber tree leaflets, in association with
Lorryia formosa Cooreman, 1958
(Acari, Tydeidae ), preying on their eggs and immatures. It was also found with
Zetzellia quasagistemas
sp. n. This species shows no difference concerning the leg chaetotaxy from
Z. quasagistemas
sp. n. , in any developmental stage.

Etymology : The specific designation is an anagram of
Agistemus
and
Zetzellia
, referring to the resemblance with male
Agistemus
and female
Zetzellia
, concerning dorsal shields.

Type material
: Holotype female (n. 5.816 ) collected from
Hevea brasiliensis Muell. Arg.
( Euphorbiaceae ), May 14, 2001 , Cedral, São Paulo, Brazil . Paratypes :
6 females
,
3 males
, 3 deutonymphs female, 2 deutonymphs male, 2 protonymphs,
5 larvae
from the same host and type locality, collected from
January to May 2001
.
